# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ocaml
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This document covers atomic types, such as integers and Booleans; predefined compound types, like strings and lists; and user-defined types, namely variants and records.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] We show how to pattern match on those types.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In OCaml, there are no type checks at runtime, and values don't change type unless explicitly converted.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This is what being statically- and strongly-typed means.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This allows safe processing of structured data.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `int` type is the default and basic integer type in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `int` type represents platform-dependent signed integers.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This means `int` does not always have the same number of bits.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It depends on underlying platform characteristics, such as processor architecture or operating system.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on `int` values are provided by the `Stdlib` and the `Int` modules.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Usually, `int` has 31 bits in 32-bit architectures and 63 in 64-bit architectures, because one bit is reserved for OCaml's runtime operation.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The standard library also provides `Int32` and `Int64` modules, which support platform-independent operations on 32- and 64-bit signed integers.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] These modules are not detailed in this tutorial.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] There are no dedicated types for unsigned integers in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Bitwise operations on `int` treat the sign bit the same as other bits.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The signed remainder operator is written `mod`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Integers in OCaml have no predefined power operator.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] OCaml does not perform any implicit type conversion between values.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Therefore, arithmetic expressions can't mix integers and floats.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Arguments are either all `int` or all `float`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Arithmetic operators on floats are not the same, and they are written with a dot suffix: `+.`, `-.`, `*.`, `/.`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on `float` are provided by the `Stdlib` and the `Float` modules.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Boolean values are represented by the type `bool`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on `bool` are provided by the `Stdlib` and the `Bool` modules.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The conjunction “and” is written `&&` and disjunction “or” is written `||`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Both are short-circuited, meaning that they don't evaluate the argument on the right if the left one's value is sufficient to decide the whole expression's value.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In OCaml, `if … then … else …` is a *conditional expression*.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The test subexpression must have type `bool`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Branches subexpressions must have the same type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Values of type `char` correspond to the 256 symbols of the Latin-1 set.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on `char` values are provided by the `Stdlib` and the `Char` modules.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The module `Uchar` provides support for Unicode characters.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Strings are immutable, meaning it is impossible to change a character's value inside a string.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Strings are finite and fixed-sized sequences of `char` values.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The string concatenation operator symbol is `^`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on `string` values are provided by the `Stdlib` and the `String` modules.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Like strings, byte sequences are finite and fixed-sized.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Each individual byte is represented by a `char` value.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Like arrays, byte sequences are mutable, meaning they can't be extended or shortened, but each component byte may be updated.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Essentially, a byte sequence (type `bytes`) is a mutable string that can't be printed.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] There is no way to write `bytes` literally, so they must be produced by a function.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on `bytes` values are provided by the `Stdlib` and the `Bytes` modules.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Only the function `Bytes.get` allows direct access to the characters contained in a byte sequence.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Unlike arrays, there is no direct access operator on byte sequences.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The memory representation of `bytes` is four times more compact than `char array`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Arrays are finite and fixed-sized sequences of values of the same type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Here arrays are `int array`, `char array`, and `string array`, but any type of data can be used in an array.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Usually, `array` is said to be a polymorphic type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Strictly speaking, it is a type operator, and it accepts a type as argument (here `int`, `char`, and `string`) to form another type (those inferred here).
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Remember, `'a` ("alpha") is a type parameter that will be replaced by another type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Like `string` and `bytes`, arrays support direct access, but the syntax is not the same.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Arrays are mutable, meaning they can't be extended or shortened, but each element may be updated.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The left-arrow `<-` is the array update operator.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Above, it means the cell at index 2 is set to value `'F'`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It is the same as writing `Array.set letter 2 'F'`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Array update is a side effect, and the unit value is returned.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on arrays are provided by the `Array` module.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] There is a dedicated tutorial on Arrays.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] As literals, lists are very much like arrays.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Here are the same previous examples turned into lists.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Like arrays, lists are finite sequences of values of the same type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] However, lists are extensible, immutable, and don't support direct access to all the values they contain.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Lists play a central role in functional programming, so they have a dedicated tutorial.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on lists are provided by the `List` module.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `List.append` function concatenates two lists.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It can be used as an operator with the symbol `@`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Together, they are the basic means to build a list and access the data it stores.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Pattern matching provides the basic means to access data stored inside a list.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In the above expressions, `[1; 2; 3]` is the value that is matched over.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Each expression between the `|` and `->` symbols is a pattern.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] They are expressions of type `list`, only formed using `[]`, `::`, and binding names that represent various shapes a list may have.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The pattern `[]` means “if the list is empty.” The pattern `x :: u` means “if the list contains data, let `x` be the first element of the list and `u` be the rest of the list.” Expressions at the right of the `->` symbol are the results returned in each corresponding case.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `option` type is also a polymorphic type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Option values can store any kind of data or represent the absence of any such data.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Option values can only be constructed in two different ways: either `None`, when no data is available, or `Some`, otherwise.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on options are provided by the `Option` module.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Options are discussed in the Error Handling guide.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `result` type can be used to express that a function's outcome can be either success or failure.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] There are only two ways to build a result value: either using `Ok` or `Error` with the intended meaning.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Both constructors can hold any kind of data.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `result` type is polymorphic, but it has two type parameters: one for `Ok` values and another for `Error` values.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Operations on results are provided by the `Result` module.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Results are discussed in the Error Handling guide.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Here is a tuple containing two values, also known as a pair.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] That pair contains the integer `3` and the character `'K'`; its type is `int * char`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `*` symbol stands for *product type*.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This generalises to tuples with 3 or more elements.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] For instance, `(6.28, true, "hello")` has type `float * bool * string`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The types `int * char` and `float * bool * string` are called *product types*.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `*` symbol is used to denote types bundled together in products.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The predefined function `fst` returns the first element of a pair, while `snd` returns the second element of a pair.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In the standard library, both are defined using pattern matching.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Note that types `int * char * bool`, `int * (char * bool)`, and `(int * char) * bool` are not the same.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In mathematical language, the product type operator `*` is not *associative*.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The type of functions from type `m` to type `n` is written `m -> n`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The first expression is an anonymous function of type `int -> int`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The type is inferred from the expression `x * x`, which must be of type `int` since `*` is an operator that returns an `int`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `<fun>` printed in place of the value is a token, meaning functions don't have a value to be displayed.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This is because, if they have been compiled, their code is no longer available.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The second expression is function application.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The argument `9` is applied, and the result `81` is returned.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The first expression is another anonymous function.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It is the *identity* function, it can be applied to anything, and it returns its argument unchanged.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This means that its argument can be of any type, and its result has the same type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The same code can be applied to data of different types.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Remember, the `'a` is a *type parameter*, so values of any type can be passed to the function and their type replaces the type parameter.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The identity function has the same input and output type, whatever it may be.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Executable OCaml code consists primarily of functions, so it's beneficial to make them as concise and clear as possible.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The function `g` is defined here using a shorter, more common, and maybe more intuitive syntax.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In OCaml, functions may terminate without returning the expected type value by throwing an exception (of type `exn`), which does not appear in its type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] There is no way to know if a function may raise an exception without inspecting its code.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Exceptions are discussed in the Error Handling guide.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Like the product type symbol `*`, the function type symbol `->` is not associative.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Uniquely, the type `unit` has only one value.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Mainly, it serves as a token when a function does not need to be passed data or doesn't have any data to return once it has completed its computation.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This happens when functions have side effects such as OS-level I/O.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Functions need to be applied to something for their computation to be triggered, and they also must return something.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] When nothing meaningful can be passed or returned, `()` should be used.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The function `read_line` reads an end-of-line terminated sequence of characters from standard input and returns it as a string.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Reading input begins when `()` is passed.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The function `print_endline` prints the string followed by a line ending on standard output.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Return of the unit value means the output request has been queued by the operating system.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] User-defined types are always introduced using the `type … = …` statement.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The keyword `type` must be written in lowercase.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The first ellipsis stands for type name and must not begin with a capital.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The second ellipsis stands for the type definition.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] These three kinds of type definitions are covered in the next three sections.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Variants are also called *tagged unions*.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] They relate to the concept of *disjoint union*.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The simplest form of a variant type corresponds to an enumerated type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It is defined by an explicit list of named values.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Defined values are called constructors and must be capitalised.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] For example, here is how variant data types could be defined to represent Dungeons & Dragons character classes and alignment.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] These kinds of variant types can also be used to represent weekdays, cardinal directions, or any other fixed-sized set of values that can be given names.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] An ordering is defined on values following the definition order (e.g., `Druid < Ranger`).
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It is possible to wrap data in constructors.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The following type has several constructors with data (e.g., `Hash of string`) and some without (e.g., `Head`).
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It represents the different means to refer to a Git revision.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] We need to pass an inspected expression to the `match … with …` construct.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The `function …` is a special form of an anonymous function that takes a parameter and forwards it to a `match … with …` construct, as shown above.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The constructor `C1` has two parameters of type `int` and `bool`, whilst the constructor `C2` has a single parameter of type `int * bool`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] A variant definition referring to itself is recursive.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] A constructor may wrap data from the type being defined.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This is the case for the following definition, which can be used to store JSON values.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Both constructors `Array` and `Object` contain values of type `json`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Functions defined using pattern matching on recursive variants are often recursive too.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Here, the last pattern uses the symbol `_`, which catches everything.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It returns `false` on all data that is neither `Array` nor `Object`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The predefined type `option` is a variant type with two constructors: `Some` and `None`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It can contain values of any type, such as `Some 42` or `Some "hola"`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The predefined type `list` is polymorphic in the same sense.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It is a variant with two constructors and can hold data of any type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The only magic here is turning constructors into symbols, which we don't cover in this tutorial.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Implicitly, product types also behave as variant types.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] `(int, bool) pair` would be written `int * bool`, and `Pair (42, true)` would be written `(42, true)`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] From the developer's perspective, everything happens as if such a type were declared for every possible product shape.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This is what allows pattern matching on products.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Even integers and floats can be seen as enumerated-like variant types, with many constructors and funky syntactic sugar, which allows pattern matching on those types.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In the end, the only type construction that does not reduce to a variant is the function arrow type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Pattern matching allows the inspection of values of any type, except functions.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It can be used to represent arbitrarily labelled binary trees.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Assuming such a tree would be labelled with integers, here is a possible way to compute the sum of its integers, using recursion and pattern matching.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In the OCaml community, as well as in the larger functional programming community, the word *polymorphism* is used loosely.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] It is applied to things working in a similar fashion with various types.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In this broad sense, several features of OCaml are polymorphic.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Each uses a particular form of polymorphism and has a name.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In summary, OCaml has several forms of polymorphism.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In most cases, the distinction between those concepts is blurred, but it is sometimes necessary to distinguish them.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Records are like tuples in that several values are bundled together.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In a tuple, elements are identified by their position in the corresponding product type.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] They are either first, second, third, or at some other position.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In a record, each element has a name and a value.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This name-value pair is known as a field.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] That's why record types must be declared before being used.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] For instance, here is the definition of a record type meant to partially represent a Dungeons & Dragons character class.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Please note that the following code is dependent upon the definitions earlier in this tutorial.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Ensure you have entered the definitions in the Enumerated Data Types section.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Values of type `character` carry the same data as inhabitants of this product: `string * int * string * character_class * character_alignment * int`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Note that records behave like single constructor variants.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Just like values, any type can be given a name.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This is mostly useful as a means of documentation or to shorten long type expressions.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Function parameters can also be given a name with pattern matching for tuples and records.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This is useful for matching variant values of parameters.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The first two patterns hold the key to how the `distrib` function works.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The first pattern is `Times (e1, Plus (e2, e3))`, which matches expressions of the form `e1 * (e2 + e3)`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The right-hand side of this first pattern is equivalent to `(e1 * e2) + (e1 * e3)`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The second pattern does the same thing, except for expressions of the form `(e1 + e2) * e3`.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The remaining patterns don't change the expressions' form, but they call the `distrib` function recursively on their subexpressions.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This ensures that all its subexpressions get multiplied out too.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The reverse operation, i.e., factorising out common subexpressions, can be implemented in a similar fashion.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The following version only works for the top-level expression.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The factorise function above introduces another feature: *guards* to each pattern.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] The conditional follows the `when`, and it means that the return code is executed only if the pattern matches and the condition in the `when` clause is satisfied.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] This tutorial has provided a comprehensive overview of OCaml's basic data types and their usage.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] We have explored the built-in types, such as integers, floats, characters, lists, tuples, and strings, and the user-defined types: records and variants.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Records and tuples are mechanisms for grouping heterogeneous data into cohesive units.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Variants are a mechanism for exposing heterogeneous data as coherent alternatives.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] In this tutorial *variants* and *products* were presented, these correspond to algebraic data types.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] At this level, a nominal type-checking algorithm is used.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Historically, this is OCaml's first type system, as it comes from the ML programming language, OCaml's ancestor.
[src:ocaml/basic-data-types] Although OCaml has other type systems, this document focused on data typed using this algorithm.
[src:ocaml/lists] A list is an ordered sequence of elements.
[src:ocaml/lists] All elements of a list in OCaml must be the same type.
[src:ocaml/lists] Lists are built into the language and have a special syntax.
[src:ocaml/lists] Note semicolons separate the elements, not commas.
[src:ocaml/lists] The type of this list of integers is `int list`.
[src:ocaml/lists] A list, if it is not empty, has a *head* (the first element) and a *tail* (the list consisting of the rest of the elements).
[src:ocaml/lists] In our example, the head is the integer `1` while the tail is the list `[2; 3]`.
[src:ocaml/lists] An empty list has neither a head nor a tail.
[src:ocaml/lists] Notice the type of the empty list is `'a list` (its element type is not known).
[src:ocaml/lists] Notice also the type of the last list - `int list list` or a list of lists of integers.
[src:ocaml/lists] There are two built-in operators on lists.
[src:ocaml/lists] The `::` or cons operator, adds one element to the front of a list.
[src:ocaml/lists] This function operates not just on lists of integers, but on any kind of list.
[src:ocaml/lists] Because in the pattern `_ :: t` the head of the list is not inspected, so its type cannot be relevant.
[src:ocaml/lists] Notice that the memory for the second list is shared, but the first list is effectively copied.
[src:ocaml/lists] We might wish to apply a function to each element in a list, yielding a new one.
[src:ocaml/lists] Notice the type of the function `f` in parentheses as part of the whole type.
[src:ocaml/lists] This `map` function, given a function of type `'a -> 'b` and a list of `'a`s, will build a list of `'b'`s.
[src:ocaml/lists] Sometimes `'a` and `'b` might be the same type, of course.
[src:ocaml/lists] The standard library List module contains a wide range of useful utility functions, including pre-written versions of many of the functions we have written in this tutorial.
[src:ocaml/lists] A version of the module with labelled functions is available as part of StdLabels.
[src:ocaml/lists] In the List module documentation, functions which can raise an exception are marked.
[src:ocaml/lists] Such exceptions are usually the result of lists which are empty (and therefore have neither a head nor a tail) or lists of mismatched length.
[src:ocaml/lists] We have already written a `map` function from scratch, and it is no surprise that one is included in the List module.
[src:ocaml/lists] In addition, we have an imperative analogue to `map`, called `iter`.
[src:ocaml/lists] It takes an imperative function of type `'a -> unit` and an `'a list` and applies the function to each element in turn.
[src:ocaml/lists] There are more elaborate scanning functions: imagine we wish to check to see if all elements of a list are even, or if any element is even.
[src:ocaml/lists] So you can see how the standard library has evolved into its present state: pieces of frequently-used code are turned into useful general functions.
[src:ocaml/lists] The function `find` returns the first element of a list matching a given predicate (a predicate is a testing function which returns either true or false when given an element).
[src:ocaml/lists] If we wish to know also which elements did not test true, we can use `partition` which returns a pair of lists: the first being the list of elements for which the predicate is true, the second those for which it is false.
[src:ocaml/lists] Note that the documentation for `filter` and `partition` tells us that the order of the input is preserved in the output.
[src:ocaml/lists] Where this is not stated it the documentation, it cannot be assumed.
[src:ocaml/lists] Association lists are a simple (and simplistic) way of implementing the dictionary data structure: that is to say, a group of keys each with an associated value.
[src:ocaml/lists] For large dictionaries, for efficiency, we would use the standard library's Map or Hashtbl modules.
[src:ocaml/lists] But these functions from the List module are useful for lists which are generally small, and have other advantages: since they are just lists of pairs, they can be built and modified easily.
[src:ocaml/lists] They are also easily printed in the toplevel.
[src:ocaml/lists] When using association lists, and for other purposes, it is sometimes useful to be able to make a list of pairs from a pair of lists and vice versa.
[src:ocaml/lists] The function `List.sort`, given a comparison function of type `'a -> 'a -> int` (zero if equal, negative if first smaller, positive if second smaller) and an input list of type `'a list`, returns the list sorted according to the comparison function.
[src:ocaml/lists] Typically, we use the built-in comparison function `compare` which can compare any two values of like type (with the exception of functions which are incomparable).
[src:ocaml/lists] The function `Fun.flip` reverses a binary function parameter order.
[src:ocaml/lists] There are two interestingly-named functions in the List module, `fold_left` and `fold_right`.
[src:ocaml/lists] Their job is to combine the elements of a list together, using a given function, accumulating an answer which is then returned.
[src:ocaml/lists] The answer returned depends upon the function given, the elements of the list, and the initial value of the accumulator supplied.
[src:ocaml/lists] So you can imagine these are very general functions.
[src:ocaml/lists] The result is the sum of the elements in the list.
[src:ocaml/lists] Now let's use OCaml's built-in `max` function which returns the larger of two given integers in place of our addition function.
[src:ocaml/lists] The largest number in the list is found.
[src:ocaml/lists] The function is of type `'a -> 'b -> 'a` where `'a` is the accumulator and `'b` is the type of each element of the list.
[src:ocaml/lists] The next parameter is the initial accumulator, which must be of type `'a`, and then finally the input list of type `'b list`.
[src:ocaml/lists] The result is the final value of the accumulator, so it must have type `'a`.
[src:ocaml/lists] Of course, in both of our examples, `'a` and `'b` are the same as one another.
[src:ocaml/lists] In this example, the initial accumulator is the second list, and each element of the first is consed to it in turn.
[src:ocaml/lists] The function comes first, then the list of elements, then the initial accumulator value.
[src:ocaml/lists] Unfortunately, the order of evaluation here is such that larger and larger items are passed to the `@` operator as its first argument, and so the function has a worse running time than `List.concat`.
[src:ocaml/lists] You can read more about the time and space efficiency of lists and other common OCaml data structures in the comparison of standard containers.
[src:ocaml/lists] Here are some more redefinitions of familiar functions in terms of `fold_left` or `fold_right`.
[src:ocaml/lists] For long lists, this may overflow the stack (be too large for the computer to handle).
[src:ocaml/lists] We call such a function *tail-recursive*.
[src:ocaml/lists] In the standard library documentation, functions which are not tail-recursive are marked.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The OCaml toolchain includes an interactive top-level interpreter, a bytecode compiler, an optimizing native code compiler, a reversible debugger, and a package manager (OPAM) together with a composable build system for OCaml (Dune).
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml was developed first in the context of automated theorem proving, and is used in static analysis and formal methods software.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Beyond these areas, it has found use in systems programming, web development, and specific financial utilities, among other application domains.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The acronym *CAML* originally stood for *Categorical Abstract Machine Language*, but OCaml omits this abstract machine.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml is a free and open-source software project managed and principally maintained by the French Institute for Research in Computer Science and Automation (Inria).
[src:ocaml/ocaml] In the early 2000s, elements from OCaml were adopted by many languages, notably F# and Scala.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] ML-derived languages are best known for their static type systems and type-inferring compilers.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml unifies functional, imperative, and object-oriented programming under an ML-like type system.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Thus, programmers need not be highly familiar with the pure functional language paradigm to use OCaml.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] By requiring the programmer to work within the constraints of its static type system, OCaml eliminates many of the type-related runtime problems associated with dynamically typed languages.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Also, OCaml's type-inferring compiler greatly reduces the need for the manual type annotations that are required in most statically typed languages.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] For example, the data types of variables and the signatures of functions usually need not be declared explicitly, as they do in languages like Java and C#, because they can be inferred from the operators and other functions that are applied to the variables and other values in the code.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Effective use of OCaml's type system can require some sophistication on the part of a programmer, but this discipline is rewarded with reliable, high-performance software.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml is perhaps most distinguished from other languages with origins in academia by its emphasis on performance.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] These are rare enough that avoiding them is quite possible in practice.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Aside from type-checking overhead, functional programming languages are, in general, challenging to compile to efficient machine language code, due to issues such as the funarg problem.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Xavier Leroy has stated that "OCaml delivers at least 50% of the performance of a decent C compiler", although a direct comparison is impossible.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Some functions in the OCaml standard library are implemented with faster algorithms than equivalent functions in the standard libraries of other languages.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Between the 1970s and 1980s, Robin Milner, a British computer scientist and Turing Award winner, worked at the University of Edinburgh's Laboratory for Foundations of Computer Science.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Milner and others were working on theorem provers, which were historically developed in languages such as Lisp.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Milner repeatedly ran into the issue that the theorem provers would attempt to claim a proof was valid by putting non-proofs together.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] As a result, he went on to develop the meta language for his Logic for Computable Functions, a language that would only allow the writer to construct valid proofs with its polymorphic type system.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] ML was turned into a compiler to simplify using LCF on different machines, and, by the 1980s, was turned into a complete system of its own.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] ML would eventually serve as a basis for the creation of OCaml.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] In the early 1980s, there were some developments that prompted INRIA's Formel team to become interested in the ML language.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Luca Cardelli, a research professor at University of Oxford, used his *functional abstract machine* to develop a faster implementation of ML, and Robin Milner proposed a new definition of ML to avoid divergence between various implementations.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Simultaneously, Pierre-Louis Curien, a senior researcher at Paris Diderot University, developed a calculus of categorical combinators and linked it to lambda calculus, which led to the definition of the *categorical abstract machine* (CAM).
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Guy Cousineau, a researcher at Paris Diderot University, recognized that this could be applied as a compiling method for ML.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Caml was designed and developed first by INRIA's Formel team headed by Gérard Huet.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The first implementation of Caml was created in 1987 and was further developed until 1992.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Though it was spearheaded by Ascánder Suárez, Pierre Weis and Michel Mauny carried on with development after he left in 1988.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Guy Cousineau is quoted recalling that his experience with programming language implementation was initially very limited, and that there were multiple inadequacies for which he is responsible.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Between 1990 and 1991, Xavier Leroy designed a new implementation of Caml based on a bytecode interpreter written in C.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] In addition to this, Damien Doligez wrote a memory management system, also known as a sequential garbage collector, for this implementation.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] This new implementation, known as Caml Light, replaced the old Caml implementation and ran on small desktop machines.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] In the following years, libraries such as Michel Mauny's syntax manipulation tools appeared and helped promote the use of Caml in educational and research teams.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] In 1995, Xavier Leroy released Caml Special Light, which was an improved version of Caml.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] An optimizing native-code compiler was added to the bytecode compiler, which greatly increased performance to comparable levels with mainstream languages such as C++.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Also, Leroy designed a high-level module system inspired by the module system of Standard ML which provided powerful facilities for abstraction and parameterization and made larger-scale programs easier to build.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Didier Rémy and Jérôme Vouillon designed an expressive type system for objects and classes, which was integrated within Caml Special Light.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] This led to the emergence of the Objective Caml language, first released in 1996 and subsequently renamed to OCaml in 2011.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] This object system notably supported many prevalent object-oriented idioms in a statically type-safe way, while those same idioms caused unsoundness or required runtime checks in languages such as C++ or Java.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] In 2000, Jacques Garrigue extended Objective Caml with multiple new features such as polymorphic methods, variants, and labeled and optional arguments.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Language improvements have been incrementally added for the last two decades to support the growing commercial and academic codebases in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The OCaml 4.0 release in 2012 added Generalized Algebraic Data Types (GADTs) and first-class modules to increase the flexibility of the language.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The OCaml 5.0.0 release in 2022 is a complete rewrite of the language runtime, removing the global GC lock and adding effect handlers via delimited continuations.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] These changes enable support for shared-memory parallelism and color-blind concurrency, respectively.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml's development continued within the Cristal team at INRIA until 2005, when it was succeeded by the Gallium team.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Subsequently, Gallium was succeeded by the Cambium team in 2019.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] As of 2023, there are 23 core developers of the compiler distribution from a variety of organizations and 41 developers for the broader OCaml tooling and packaging ecosystem.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] In 2023, the OCaml compiler was recognised with ACM SIGPLAN's Programming Languages Software Award.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml features a static type system, type inference, parametric polymorphism, tail recursion, pattern matching, first class lexical closures, functors (parametric modules), exception handling, effect handling, and incremental generational automatic garbage collection.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml is notable for extending ML-style type inference to an object system in a general-purpose language.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] This permits structural subtyping, where object types are compatible if their method signatures are compatible, regardless of their declared inheritance (an unusual feature in statically typed languages).
[src:ocaml/ocaml] A foreign function interface for linking to C primitives is provided, including language support for efficient numerical arrays in formats compatible with both C and Fortran.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml also supports creating libraries of OCaml functions that can be linked to a *main* program in C, so that an OCaml library can be distributed to C programmers who have no knowledge or installation of OCaml.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Although OCaml does not have a macro system as an indivisible part of the language (metaprogramming), i.e. built-in support for preprocessing, the OCaml platform does officially support a library for writing such preprocessors.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] These can be of two types: one that works at the source code level (as in C), and one that works on the Abstract Syntax Tree level.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The latter, which is called PPX, acronym for Pre-Processor eXtension, is the recommended one.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The native code compiler is available for many platforms, including Unix, Microsoft Windows, and Apple macOS.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The bytecode compiler supports operation on any 32- or 64-bit architecture when native code generation is not available, requiring only a C compiler.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml bytecode and native code programs can be written in a multithreaded style, with preemptive context switching.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml threads in the same domain execute by time sharing only.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] However, an OCaml program can contain several domains.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Snippets of OCaml code are most easily studied by entering them into the *top-level REPL*.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] This is an interactive OCaml session that prints the inferred types of resulting or defined expressions.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Code can then be entered at the "#" prompt.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml infers the type of the expression to be "int" (a machine-precision integer) and gives the result "7".
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The first argument to ocamlc, "hello.ml", specifies the source file to compile and the "-o hello" flag specifies the output file.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The `option` type constructor in OCaml, similar to the `Maybe` type in Haskell, augments a given data type to either return `Some` value of the given data type, or to return `None`.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] This is used to express that a value might or might not be present.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Lists are one of the fundamental datatypes in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The following code example defines a recursive function *sum* that accepts one argument, *integers*, which is supposed to be a list of integers.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Note the keyword `rec` which denotes that the function is recursive.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The function recursively iterates over the given list of integers and provides a sum of the elements.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The *match* statement has similarities to C's switch element, though it is far more general.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Another way is to use standard fold function that works with lists.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] OCaml lends itself to concisely expressing recursive algorithms.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The following code example implements an algorithm similar to quicksort that sorts a list in increasing order.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Or using partial application of the >= operator.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The following program calculates the smallest number of people in a room for whom the probability of completely unique birthdays is less than 50% (the birthday problem, where for 1 person the probability is 365/365 (or 100%), for 2 it is 364/365, for 3 it is 364/365 × 363/365, etc.) (answer = 23).
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The following code defines a Church encoding of natural numbers, with successor (succ) and addition (add).
[src:ocaml/ocaml] A Church numeral `n` is a higher-order function that accepts a function `f` and a value `x` and applies `f` to `x` exactly `n` times.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] To convert a Church numeral from a functional value to a string, we pass it a function that prepends the string `"S"` to its input and the constant string `"0"`.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The given example outputs the Church numeral for five as “SSSSS0”.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] A variety of libraries are directly accessible from OCaml.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] For example, OCaml has a built-in library for arbitrary-precision arithmetic.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] As the factorial function grows very rapidly, it quickly overflows machine-precision numbers (typically 32- or 64-bits).
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Thus, factorial is a suitable candidate for arbitrary-precision arithmetic.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The LablGL bindings to OpenGL are required.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Far more sophisticated, high-performance 2D and 3D graphical programs can be developed in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Thanks to the use of OpenGL and OCaml, the resulting programs can be cross-platform, compiling without any changes on many major platforms.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The following code calculates the Fibonacci sequence of a number *n* inputted.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] It uses tail recursion and pattern matching.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Functions may take functions as input and return functions as result.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] For example, applying *twice* to a function *f* yields a function that applies *f* two times to its argument.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The function *twice* uses a type variable*'a* to indicate that it can be applied to any function *f* mapping from a type*'a* to itself, rather than only to *int->int* functions.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] In particular, *twice* can even be applied to itself.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] MetaOCaml is a multi-stage programming extension of OCaml enabling incremental compiling of new machine code during runtime.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] Under some circumstances, significant speedups are possible using multistage programming, because more detailed information about the data to process is available at runtime than at the regular compile time, so the incremental compiler can optimize away many cases of condition checking, etc.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] The new function is automatically compiled.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] At least several dozen companies use OCaml to some degree.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] In the context of academic teaching and research, OCaml has a remarkable presence in computer science teaching programmes, both in universities and colleges.
[src:ocaml/ocaml] A list of educational resources and these teaching programmes can be found at ocaml.org.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This tutorial introduces OCaml's basic features: values, expressions, lists, functions, pattern matching, and more.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] No OCaml or any functional programming knowledge is required; however, it is assumed the reader has some basic software development knowledge.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Please ensure you've installed OCaml and set up the environment, as described on the Install OCaml page.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] We recommend that you execute the examples we provide, and to experiment with them, to get a feel for coding in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] To do this, you can use UTop (Universal Toplevel).
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] UTop allows users to interact with OCaml by reading and evaluating OCaml phrases, like expressions or value definitions, and printing the result on the screen.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] For more information, you can read the Introduction to the OCaml Toplevel.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Some of the examples in this tour include comments.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Comments in OCaml start with `(*` and end with `*)` and can be nested.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Since they are ignored by OCaml, they can be used anywhere whitespace is permitted.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] When entering the code below into UTop, the comments can be left out.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In OCaml, everything has a value, and every value has a type.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The above example says, “`50 * 50` is an expression that has type `int` (integer) and evaluates to `2500`.” Since it is an anonymous expression, the character `-` appears instead of a name.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The double semicolon `;;` at the end tells the toplevel to evaluate and print the result of the given phrase.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It automatically determines the type of an expression without much guidance from the programmer.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] For the time being, the following two expressions are both lists.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The former contains integers, and the latter, strings.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The lists' types, `int list` and `string list`, have been inferred from the type of their elements.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Lists can be empty `[]` (pronounced “nil”).
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Note that the first list has been given a name using the `let … = …` construction, which is detailed below.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The most primitive operation on lists is to add a new element at the front of an existing list.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This is done using the “cons” operator, written with the double colon operator `::`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In OCaml, `if … then … else …` is not a statement; it is an expression.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The source beginning at `if` and ending at `5` is parsed as a single integer expression that is multiplied by 2.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] OCaml has no need for two different test constructions.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The ternary conditional operator and the `if … then … else …` are the same.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Also note parentheses are not needed here, which is often the case in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Values can be given names using the `let` keyword.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This is called *binding* a value to a name.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] When entering `let x = 50;;`, OCaml responds with `val x : int = 50`, meaning that `x` is an identifier bound to value `50`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Bindings in OCaml are *immutable*, meaning that the value assigned to a name never changes.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Although `x` is often called a variable, it is not the case.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Using over-simplifying but acceptable words, all variables are immutable in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It is possible to give names to values that can be updated.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In OCaml, this is called a *reference* and will be discussed in the Working With Mutable State section.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] There is no overloading in OCaml, so inside a lexical scope, names have a single value, which only depends on its definition.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Do not use dashes in names; use underscores instead.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] For example: `x_plus_y` works, `x-plus-y` does not.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Bindings can be given special comments (sometimes called "docstrings") that editors and tooling treat as related to the binding.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] These are denoted by adding a second `*` to the opening of the comment.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This is discussed further in `odoc` for Authors: Special Comments.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This example defines the name `y` and binds it to the value `50`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It is then used in the expression `y * y`, resulting in the value `2500`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Note that `y` is only defined in the expression following the `in` keyword.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This defines two names: `a` with value `1` and `b` with value `2`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Then the example uses them in the expression `a + b`, resulting in the value of `3`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In OCaml, the equality symbol has two meanings.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It is used in definitions and equality tests.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This is interpreted as: “define `dummy` as the result of the structural equality test between the strings `"hi"` and `"hello"`.” OCaml also has a double equal operator `==`, which stands for physical equality, but it is not used in this tutorial.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The operator `<>` is the negation of `=`, while `!=` is the negation of `==`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In OCaml, since everything is a value, functions are values too.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This example defines a function named `square` with the single parameter `x`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Its *function body* is the expression `x * x`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] When `square` is applied to `50`, it evaluates `x * x` into `50 * 50`, which leads to `2500`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The REPL indicates that the type of `square` is `int -> int`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This means it is a function taking an `int` as argument (input) and returning an `int` as result (output).
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] A function value can't be displayed, which is why `<fun>` is printed instead.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Some functions, such as `String.ends_with` have labelled parameters.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Labels are useful when a function has several parameters of the same type; naming arguments allows to guess their purpose.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Above, `~suffix:"less"` indicates `"less"` is passed as labelled argument `suffix`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Labelled arguments are detailed in the Labelled Arguments tutorial.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] A function may have several parameters, separated by spaces.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The function `cat` has two `string` parameters, `a` and `b`, and returns a value of type `string`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Functions don't have to be called with all the arguments they expect.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It is possible to only pass `a` to `cat` without passing `b`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This returns a function that expects a single string, here the `b` from the definition of `cat`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In the above, `cat` was partially applied to `"hi"`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] A function may expect a function as a parameter, which is called a *higher-order* function.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] A well-known example of higher-order function is `List.map`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The name of this function begins with `List.` because it is part of the predefined library of functions acting on lists.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This matter will be discussed more later.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Function `List.map` has two parameters: the second is a list, and the first is a function that can be applied to the list's elements, whatever they may be.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] `List.map` returns a list formed by applying the function provided as argument to each of the elements of the input list.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The function `List.map` can be applied on any kind of list.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Here it is given a list of integers, but it could be a list of floats, strings, or anything.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The `List.map` function is polymorphic, meaning it has two implicit *type variables*: `'a` and `'b` (pronounced “alpha” and “beta”).
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Output list elements have the same type as its output.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Performing operating system level input-output operations is done using functions.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The function `read_line` reads characters on standard input and returns them as a string when end-of-line (EOL) is reached.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The function `print_endline` prints a string on standard output, followed by an EOL.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The function `read_line` doesn't need any data to proceed, and the function `print_endline` doesn't have any meaningful data to return.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Indicating this absence of data is the role of the `unit` type, which appears in their signature.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The type `unit` has a single value, written `()` and pronounced “unit.” It is used as a placeholder when no data is passed or returned, but some token still has to be passed to start processing or indicate processing has terminated.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Input-output is an example of something taking place when executing a function but which does not appear in the function type.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This is called a *side-effect* and does not stop at I/O.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The `unit` type is often used to indicate the presence of side-effects, although it's not always the case.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] A recursive function calls itself in its own body.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Such functions must be declared using `let rec … = …` instead of just `let`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Recursion is not the only means to perform iterative computation on OCaml.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Loops such as `for` and `while` are available, but they are meant to be used when writing imperative OCaml in conjunction with mutable data.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Otherwise, recursive functions should be preferred.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Here is an example of a function which creates a list of consecutive integers between two bounds.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] As indicated by its type `int -> int -> int list`, the function `range` takes two integers as arguments and returns a list of integers as result.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The first `int` parameter, `lo`, is the range's lower bound; the second `int` parameter, `hi`, is the higher bound.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] If `lo > hi`, the empty range is returned.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] That's the first branch of the `if … then … else` expression.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Otherwise, the `lo` value is prepended to the list created by calling `range` itself; this is recursion.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Prepending is achieved using `::`, the cons operator in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It constructs a new list by adding an element at the front of an existing list.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Progress is made at each call; since `lo` has just been prepended at the head of the list, `range` is called with `lo + 1`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Each `=>` sign corresponds to the computation of a recursive step, except the last one.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] OCaml handles lists internally, as shown in the penultimate expression, but displays them as the last expression.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] No computation takes place between the two last steps.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] OCaml has floating-point values of type `float`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In OCaml, `+.` is the addition between floats, while `+` is the addition between integers.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In many programming languages, values can be automatically converted from one type into another.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This includes *implicit type conversion* and *promotion*.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] For example, in such a language, if you write `1 + 2.5`, the first argument (an integer) is promoted to a floating point number, making the result a floating point number, too.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] OCaml never implicitly converts values from one type to another.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It is not possible to perform the addition of a float and integer.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In the first example, `+` is intended to be used with integers, so it can't be used with the `2.5` float.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In the second example, `+.` is intended to be used with floats, so it can't be used with the `1` integer.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] There are several reasons why OCaml requires explicit conversions.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Most importantly, it enables types to be worked out automatically.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] OCaml's *type inference* algorithm computes a type for each expression and requires very little annotation, in comparison to other languages.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Arguably, this saves more time than we lose by being more explicit.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Lists may be the most common data type in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] They are ordered collections of values having the same type.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] A list containing the Booleans `false`, `false`, and `true`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Lists are defined as being either empty, written `[]`, or being an element `x` added at the front of another list `u`, which is written `x :: u` (the double colon operator is pronounced “cons”).
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In OCaml, *pattern matching* provides a means to inspect data of any kind, except functions.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In this section, it is introduced on lists, and it will be generalised to other data types in the next section.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Note that the `x :: v` pattern in the second matching expression is used to destructure the list into its head `x` and tail `v`, where *head* is the first element of the list and *tail* is the rest of the list.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This function operates not just on lists of integers but on any kind of list.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Its type indicates input of type `'a list` where `'a` is a type variable standing for any type.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The empty list pattern `[]` can be of any element type.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] So the `_ :: v` pattern, as the value at the head of the list, is irrelevant because the `_` pattern indicates it is not inspected.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Since both patterns must be of the same type, the typing algorithm infers the `'a list -> int` type.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It is possible to pass a function as argument to another function.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Functions having other functions as parameters are called *higher-order* functions.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This was illustrated earlier using function `List.map`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Here is how `map` can be written using pattern matching on lists.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Pattern matching isn't limited to lists.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Any kind of data can be inspected using it, except functions.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Patterns are expressions that are compared to an inspected value.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It could be performed using `if … then … else …`, but pattern matching is more convenient.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Here is an example using the `option` data type that will be detailed in the Modules and the Standard Library section.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The inspected value is `opt` of type `option`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It is compared against the patterns from top to bottom.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] If `opt` is the `None` option, it is a match with the first pattern.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] If `opt` is the `Some None` option, it's a match with the second pattern.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] If `opt` is a double-wrapped option with a value, it's a match with the third pattern.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Patterns can introduce names, just as `let` does.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In the third pattern, `x` designates the data inside the double-wrapped option.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Pattern matching is detailed in the Basic Datatypes tutorial as well as in per data type tutorials.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In this other example, the same comparison is made, using `if … then … else …` and pattern matching.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The underscore symbol is a catch-all pattern; it matches with anything.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Tuples are fixed-length collections of elements of any type.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Pairs are tuples that have two elements.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Access to the components of tuples is done using pattern matching.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Note: The function `snd` is predefined in the OCaml standard library.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The type of tuples is written using `*` between the components' types.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Like pattern matching generalises `switch` statements, variant types generalise enumerated and union types.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In the previous definitions, the capitalised identifiers are called *constructors*.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] They allow the creation of variant values.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This is unrelated to object-oriented programming.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] As suggested in the first sentence of this section, variants go along with pattern matching.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Like a function, a variant can be recursive if it refers to itself in its own definition.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] As previously shown, `sum`, `length`, and `map` functions provide examples of pattern matching over the list variant type.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Like tuples, records also pack elements of several types together.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Like variant types, records types must be defined before being used.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Here are examples of a record type, a value, access to a component, and pattern matching on the same record.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] When defining `gerard`, no type needs to be declared.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The type checker will search for a record which has exactly three fields with matching names and types.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Note that there are no typing relationships between records.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It is not possible to declare a record type that extends another by adding fields.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Record type search will succeed if it finds an exact match and fails in any other case.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Here, the pattern `{ age = x; _ }` is typed with the most recently declared record type that has an `age` field of type `int`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The type `int` is inferred from the expression `13 <= x && x <= 19`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The function `is_teenager` will only work with the found record type, here `person`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] When a computation is interrupted, an exception is thrown.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Exceptions are raised using the `raise` function.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Note that exceptions do not appear in function types.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The standard library provides several predefined exceptions.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Another way to deal with errors in OCaml is by returning a value of type `result`, which can represent either the correct result or an error.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Usually, the `let … = …` syntax does not define variables, it defines constants.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] However, mutable variables exist in OCaml.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It is syntactically impossible to create an uninitialised or null reference.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The `r` reference is initialised with the integer zero.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Accessing a reference's content is done using the `!` de-reference operator.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Note that `!r` and `r` have different types: `int` and `int ref`, respectively.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Just like it is not possible to perform multiplication of an integer and a float, it is not possible to update an integer or multiply a reference.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Here `:=` is the assignment operator; it is pronounced “receives”.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This returns `()` because changing the content of a reference is a side-effect.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Execute an expression after another with the `;` operator.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Once done, execute `b`, only returns the value of `b`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This behaviour is the same as in an imperative language.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] However, although `;` is not defined as a function, it behaves as if it were a function of type `unit -> unit -> unit`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Organising source code in OCaml is done using something called *modules*.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The *standard library* is a set of modules available to all OCaml programs.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Definitions provided by modules are referred to by adding the module name as a prefix to their name.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Here, usage of the function `Option.map` is illustrated in several steps.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Using partial application, only pass `fun x -> x * x`.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Check the type of the resulting function.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] When the option value provided contains an actual value (i.e., it is `Some` something), it applies the provided function and returns its result wrapped in an option.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] When the option value provided doesn't contain anything (i.e., it is `None`), the result doesn't contain anything as well (i.e., it is `None` too).
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The `List.map` function which was used earlier in this section is also part of a module, the `List` module.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This illustrates the first feature of the OCaml module system.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] It provides a means to separate concerns by preventing name clashes.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Two functions having different type may have the same name if they are provided by different modules.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] Modules also allow for efficient separate compilation.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] This is illustrated in the next tutorial.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] In this tutorial, OCaml was used interactively.
[src:ocaml/tour-of-ocaml] The next tutorial, Your First OCaml Program, shows you how to write OCaml files, how to compile them, and how to kickstart a project.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In OCaml, functions are treated as values, so you can use functions as arguments to functions and return them from functions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This tutorial introduces the relationship between expressions, values, and names.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The first four sections address non-function values.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The following sections, starting at Function as Values, address functions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] We use UTop to understand these concepts by example.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] You are encouraged to modify the examples to gain a better understanding.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Like most functional programming languages, OCaml is an expression-oriented programming language.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Actually, almost everything is an expression.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In OCaml, statements don't specify actions to be taken on data.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] All computations are made through expression evaluation.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Below, you'll find a few examples of expressions, their types, and the resulting values.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] An expression's type (before evaluation) and its resulting value's type (after computation) are the same.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This allows the compiler to avoid runtime type checks in binaries.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In OCaml, the compiler removes type information, so it's not available at runtime.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In programming theory, this is called subject reduction.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This is the purpose of the `let … = …` statement.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The name is on the left; the expression is on the right.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Global definitions are those entered at the top level.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Local definitions are introduced by the `let … = … in …` expression.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The name bound before the `in` keyword is only bound in the expression after the `in` keyword.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Here, the name `d` is bound to `6` inside the expression `d * 7`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Local definitions can be chained (one after another) or nested (one inside another).
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Arbitrary combinations of chaining or nesting are allowed.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In both examples, `d` and `e` are local definitions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Pattern matching is a programming language construct that generalizes case analysis, it makes subexpression inspection possible and applies to values of any type.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In the following sections, we explore matching inside `let` bindings, which is a special case.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In the next chapter on Basic Data Types and Pattern Matching, we examine pattern matching in general cases using `match...with`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The chapter on Error Handling explores how destructuring values aids in error handling when using `try...with`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] When pattern matching only has one case, it can be used in name definitions and in `let ... =` and `fun ... ->` expressions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In that case, less or more than one name may be defined.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This applies to tuples, records, and custom single-variant types.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It allows the creation of two names with a single `let`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The `List.split` function turns a list of pairs into a pair of lists.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Here, each resulting list is bound to a name.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Single-case pattern matching can also be used for parameter declaration.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Above, the pattern does not contain any identifier, meaning no name is defined.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The expression is evaluated and the side effect takes place (printing `ha ha` to standard output).
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This also works with user-defined types.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Pattern matching also works with nested user-defined types.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In the following example, we deconstruct a tuple nested within a record.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Records require explicit type definitions wherein field names are annotated with types.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The following examples demonstrate two methods by which we can extract Jane's `email` and `phone` number data in the nested `contact` tuple.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] We will do so first by using nested deconstruction, then demonstrate another approach by first extracting `content` followed by accessing the `email` and `phone` by deconstructing `contact`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This is because "contact" is not a top-level definition; rather, it is a local definition from deconstructive pattern-matching.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Next, we demonstrate the two-phase approach for accessing `email` and `phone`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] When pattern matching, it is possible to discard or ignore values that are not desired.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The method by which this is done depends on the data structure being destructured.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Tuples behave differently from records; contained data is anonymous, and its position is used to access it.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Without oversimplifying, an OCaml program is a sequence of expressions or global `let` definitions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Execution evaluates each item from top to bottom.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] At any time during evaluation, the *environment* is the ordered sequence of available definitions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The *environment* is also known as *context* in other languages.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Here, the name `twenty` is added to the top-level environment.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This name is available anywhere after the definition.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Evaluating `ten` results in an error because it hasn't been added to the global environment.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] However, in the expression `2 * ten`, the local environment contains the definition of `ten`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Although OCaml is an expression-oriented language, it has a few statements.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The global `let` modifies the global environment by adding a name-value *binding*.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Top-level expressions are also statements because they are equivalent to `let _ =` definitions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Once you create a name, define it, and bind it to a value, it does not change.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The second definition *shadows* the first.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Inner shadowing is limited to the local definition's scope.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Therefore, anything written after will still take the previous definition, as shown above.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It's still `21`, as defined in the first expression.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The second expression binds `i` locally, inside `i * 2`, not globally.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Another kind of shadowing takes place when there are two definitions with the same name at the same level.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] There are now two definitions of `h` in the environment.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] When the second `h` is defined, the first one becomes unreachable.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This is the key concept of functional programming.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In this context, it is also possible to say that OCaml has first-class functions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] When several expressions are written side by side, the leftmost one should be a function.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In OCaml, no parentheses are needed to express passing an argument to a function.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Parentheses serve a single purpose: associating expressions to create subexpressions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] When creating subexpressions, using `begin ... end` is also possible.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This is the same as using brackets `( ... )`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Some functions, such as `String.starts_with` have labelled parameters.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Above, `~prefix:"state"` indicates `"state"` is passed as labelled argument `prefix`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Labelled and optional parameters are detailed in the Labelled Arguments tutorial.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] There are two alternative ways to apply functions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The `@@` application operator applies an argument (on the right) to a function (on the left).
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It is useful when chaining several calls, as it avoids writing parentheses, which creates easier-to-read code.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The pipe operator (`|>`) also avoids parentheses but in reversed order: function on right, argument on left.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Functions don't have to be bound to a name unless they are recursive.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Function values not bound to names are called *anonymous functions*.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Anonymous functions are often passed as arguments to other functions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] You can globally bind a function to a name using a global definition.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The expression, which happens to be a function, is turned into value and bound to a name.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The former explicitly binds the anonymous function to a name.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The latter uses a more compact syntax and avoids the `fun` keyword and the arrow symbol.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Calling `sq` gets an error because it was only defined locally.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The function `sq` is only available inside the `sq 7 * sq 7` expression.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Although local functions are often defined inside the function's scope, this is not a requirement.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It has a single parameter `x` and returns the value of `x * j`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Although the new definition of `j` *shadows* the first one, the original remains the one the function `k` uses.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The `k` function's environment captures the first value of `j`, so every time you apply `k` (even after the second definition of `j`), you can be confident the function will behave the same.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Partially applying arguments to a function also creates a new closure.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Inside the `max_42` function, the environment contains an additional binding between the first parameter of `max` and the value 42.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In order to perform iterated computations, a function may call itself.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This is a classic (and very inefficient) way to compute Fibonacci numbers.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The number of recursive calls created doubles at each call, which creates exponential growth.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In OCaml, recursive functions must be defined and explicitly declared by using `let rec`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It is not possible to accidentally create a recursive function, and recursive functions can't be anonymous.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The first version `fib_loop` has two extra parameters: the two previously computed Fibonacci numbers.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The second version `fib` uses the first two Fibonacci numbers as initial values.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] There is nothing to be computed when returning from a recursive call, so this enables the compiler to perform an optimisation called tail call elimination.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Observe `sweet_cat` and `sour_cat` have the same body: `x ^ " " ^ y`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Also observe that `sweet_cat` and `sour_cat` have the same type: `string -> string -> string`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] If you check the assembly code generated using compiler explorer, you'll see it is the same for both functions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The way `sour_cat` is written corresponds more explicitly to the behaviour of both functions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The name `sour_cat` is bound to an anonymous function having parameter `x` and returning an anonymous function having parameter `y` and returning `x ^ " " ^ y`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The way `sweet_cat` is written is an abbreviated version of `sour_cat`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Such a way of shortening syntax is called syntactic sugar.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] We want to define functions of type `string -> string` that append `"kitty "` in front of its arguments.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Since a multiple-parameter function is a series of nested single-argument functions, you don't have to pass all arguments at once.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Passing a single argument to `sour_kitty` or `sweet_kitty` returns a function of type `string -> string`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The first argument, here `"kitty"`, is captured and the result is a closure.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Here the type annotation `: string -> (string -> string)` is used to explicitly state the type of `dummy_cat`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] However, OCaml answers claiming the fresh definition has type `string -> string -> string`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This is because types `string -> string -> string` and `string -> (string -> string)` are the same.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] With parentheses, it is obvious that a multiple-argument function is a single-parameter function that returns an anonymous function with one parameter removed.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Functions having type `(string -> string) -> string` take a function as a parameter.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The function `sweet_cat` has a function as a result, not a function as a parameter.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The type arrow operator *associates to the right*.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Function types without parentheses should be treated as if they have parentheses to the right in the same way that the type of `dummy_cat` was declared above.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In OCaml, a *tuple* is a data structure used to group a fixed number of values, which can be of different types.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Tuples are surrounded by parentheses, and the elements are separated by commas.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It is possible to use the tuple syntax to specify function parameters.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It looks like two arguments have been passed: `"hello"` and `"world"`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] However, only one, the `("hello", "world")` tuple, has been passed.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Inspection of the generated assembly would show it isn't the same function as `sweet_cat`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The contents of the tuple passed to `spicy_cat` (`x` and `y`) must be extracted before evaluation of the `x ^ " " ^ y` expression.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This is the role of the additional assembly instructions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In many imperative languages, the `spicy_cat ("hello", "world")` syntax reads as a function call with two arguments; but in OCaml, it denotes applying the function `spicy_cat` to a tuple containing `"hello"` and `"world"`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In the previous sections, two kinds of multiple-parameter functions have been presented.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Interestingly, both kinds of functions provide a way to pass several pieces of data while being functions with a single parameter.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It is always possible to translate back and forth between functions that look like `sweet_cat` (or `sour_cat`) and functions that look like `spicy_cat`.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It also said that `sweet_cat` and `sour_cat` are *curried* functions whilst `spicy_cat` is *uncurried*.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] These translations are attributed to the 20th-century logician Haskell Curry.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Here, this is shown using `string` as an example, but it applies to any group of three types.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] You can change the curried form into the uncurried form when refactoring, or the other way round.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] To explain side effects, we need to define what *domain* and *codomain* are.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In other words, the *domain* is left of the `->` and the *codomain* is on the right.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] These terms help avoid saying the "type at the right" or "type at the left" of a function's type arrow.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Some functions operate on data outside of their domain or codomain.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This behaviour is called an effect, or a side effect.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Doing input and output (I/O) with the operating system is the most common form of side effects.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The result of functions returning random numbers (such as `Random.bits` does) or the current time (such as `Unix.time` does) is influenced by external factors, which is also called an effect.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Similarly, any observable phenomena triggered by the computation of a function is an out-of-codomain output.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In practice, what is considered an effect is an engineering choice.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In most circumstances, system I/O operations are considered as effects, unless they are ignored.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The heat emitted by the processor when computing a function isn't usually considered a relevant side-effect, except when considering energy-efficient design.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] In the OCaml community, as well as in the wider functional programming community, functions are often said to be either pure or impure.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The former does not have side effects, the latter does.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This distinction makes sense and is useful.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Knowing what the effects are, and when are they taking place, is a key design consideration.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] However, it is important to remember this distinction always assumes some sort of context.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Any computation has effects, and what is considered a relevant effect is a design choice.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Since, by definition, effects lie outside function types, a function type can't reflect a function's possible effects.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] However, it is important to document a function's intended side effects.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It returns the number of seconds elapsed since January 1, 1970.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The result of the `Unix.time` function is determined only by external factors.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] To perform the side effect, the function must be applied to an argument.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Since no data needs to be passed, the argument is the `()` value.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] It prints the string it was passed to standard output, followed by a line termination.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Since the purpose of the function is only to produce an effect, it has no meaningful data to return; it returns the `()` value.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This illustrates the relationship between functions that have side effects and the `unit` type.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The presence of the `unit` type does not indicate the presence of side effects.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The absence of the `unit` type does not indicate the absence of side effects.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] But when no data needs to be passed as input or can be returned as output, the `unit` type is used.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] At the heart of OCaml lies the concept of the environment.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] The environment works as an ordered, append-only, key-value store.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] This means that items cannot be removed.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Furthermore, it maintains order by preserving the sequence of available definitions.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] When we use a `let` statement, we introduce zero, one, or more name-value pairs into the environment.
[src:ocaml/values-and-functions] Similarly, when applying a function to some arguments, we extend the environment by adding names and values corresponding to its arguments.
